  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions is complex and has evolved significantly over time. Here's a brief overview:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Informal methods of concealing illicit financial gains existed for centuries\n- Formal legal concepts began developing in the early 20th century\n\n2. United States Developments:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) - First major legislation requiring financial institutions to report large cash transactions\n- Racketeer Influenced and Corrupt Organizations Act (RICO) (1970) - Enhanced ability to prosecute financial crimes\n- Money Laundering Control Act (1986) - Established money laundering as a federal criminal offense\n\n3. International Developments:\n- Vienna Convention (1988) - Focused on drug trafficking proceeds\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Palermo Convention (2000) - Expanded international cooperation against organized crime\n\n4. Post-9/11 Legislation:\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) - Significantly expanded anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Increased international information sharing\n- Stricter reporting requirements for financial institutions\n\n5. Ongoing Global Efforts:\n- Continuous refinement of legal frameworks\n- Enhanced international collaboration\n- Increasing use of technology in detecting financial crimes",
